## Choosing the Right Title for Your Group

Not every game fits every group. Competitive friends will enjoy Arizona Sunshine 2 and Pistol Whip. Mixed skill levels do best with Elven Assassin and Walkabout Mini Golf. Strategy lovers will gravitate toward Demeo. High-energy groups thrive in After the Fall and Pistol Whip. VR newcomers should start with Walkabout Mini Golf or Elven Assassin.

If your group includes people who've never tried VR, start with something accessible. Elven Assassin and Walkabout Mini Golf are both excellent entry points that don't require any prior experience.

## Tips for Getting the Most Out of a Group VR Session

Communicate constantly. The best multiplayer VR sessions are loud. Call out enemies, warn teammates, celebrate good shots. The social layer is the point.

Let newcomers lead. If someone is trying VR for the first time, let them pick the first game. Their reaction to the experience is part of the fun for everyone else.

Mix formats. A full evening of VR alone can get repetitive. Combining it with physical challenge rooms or arcade games keeps the energy varied and gives everyone something to talk about on the way home.

Book ahead for larger groups. Walk-ins work well for smaller groups, but if you're bringing six or more people, booking online means you get the time slot and format you actually want.

